# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: eigenvalue-solvers
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/arnoldi-iteration] In numerical linear algebra, the **Arnoldi iteration** is an eigenvalue algorithm and an important example of an iterative method.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/arnoldi-iteration] Arnoldi finds an approximation to the eigenvalues and eigenvectors of general (possibly non-Hermitian) matrices by constructing an orthonormal basis of the Krylov subspace, which makes it particularly useful when dealing with large sparse matrices.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/arnoldi-iteration] The Arnoldi method belongs to a class of linear algebra algorithms that give a partial result after a small number of iterations, in contrast to so-called *direct methods* which must complete to give any useful results (see for example, Householder transformation).
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/arnoldi-iteration] The partial result in this case being the first few vectors of the basis the algorithm is building.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/arnoldi-iteration] When applied to Hermitian matrices it reduces to the Lanczos algorithm.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/arnoldi-iteration] The Arnoldi iteration was invented by W.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/arnoldi-iteration] An intuitive method for finding the largest (in absolute value) eigenvalue of a given *m* × *m* matrix A is the power iteration: starting with an arbitrary initial vector *b*, calculate *Ab*, *A*2*b*, *A*3*b*, ... normalizing the result after every application of the matrix *A*.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/arnoldi-iteration] This sequence converges to the eigenvector corresponding to the eigenvalue with the largest absolute value, $\lambda _{1}$ .
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/arnoldi-iteration] However, much potentially useful computation is wasted by using only the final result, $A^{n-1}b$ .
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/arnoldi-iteration] The columns of this matrix are not in general orthogonal, but we can extract an orthogonal basis, via a method such as Gram–Schmidt orthogonalization.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/arnoldi-iteration] The resulting set of vectors is thus an orthogonal basis of the *Krylov subspace*, ${\mathcal {K}}_{n}$ .
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/arnoldi-iteration] We may expect the vectors of this basis to span good approximations of the eigenvectors corresponding to the n largest eigenvalues, for the same reason that $A^{n-1}b$ approximates the dominant eigenvector.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/arnoldi-iteration] The Arnoldi iteration uses the modified Gram–Schmidt process to produce a sequence of orthonormal vectors, *q*1, *q*2, *q*3, ..., called the *Arnoldi vectors*, such that for every *n*, the vectors *q*1, ..., *q**n* span the Krylov subspace ${\mathcal {K}}_{n}$ .
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/arnoldi-iteration] The *j*-loop projects out the component of $q_{k}$ in the directions of $q_{1},\dots ,q_{k-1}$ .
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/arnoldi-iteration] This ensures the orthogonality of all the generated vectors.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/arnoldi-iteration] The algorithm breaks down when *q**k* is the zero vector.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/arnoldi-iteration] This happens when the minimal polynomial of *A* is of degree *k*.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/arnoldi-iteration] In most applications of the Arnoldi iteration, including the eigenvalue algorithm below and GMRES, the algorithm has converged at this point.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/arnoldi-iteration] Every step of the *k*-loop takes one matrix-vector product and approximately 4*mk* floating point operations.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/arnoldi-iteration] The orthogonalization method has to be specifically chosen such that the lower Arnoldi/Krylov components are removed from higher Krylov vectors.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/arnoldi-iteration] The matrix *H**n* can be viewed as *A* in the subspace ${\mathcal {K}}_{n}$ with the Arnoldi vectors as an orthogonal basis; *A* is orthogonally projected onto ${\mathcal {K}}_{n}$ .
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/arnoldi-iteration] The matrix *H**n* can be characterized by the following optimality condition.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/arnoldi-iteration] The characteristic polynomial of *H**n* minimizes ||*p*(*A*)*q*1||2 among all monic polynomials of degree *n*.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/arnoldi-iteration] This optimality problem has a unique solution if and only if the Arnoldi iteration does not break down.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/arnoldi-iteration] is an (*n*+1)-by-*n* matrix formed by adding an extra row to *H**n*.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/arnoldi-iteration] The idea of the Arnoldi iteration as an eigenvalue algorithm is to compute the eigenvalues in the Krylov subspace.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/arnoldi-iteration] The eigenvalues of *H**n* are called the *Ritz eigenvalues*.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/arnoldi-iteration] Since *H**n* is a Hessenberg matrix of modest size, its eigenvalues can be computed efficiently, for instance with the QR algorithm, or somewhat related, Francis' algorithm.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/arnoldi-iteration] Also Francis' algorithm itself can be considered to be related to power iterations, operating on nested Krylov subspace.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/arnoldi-iteration] In fact, the most basic form of Francis' algorithm appears to be to choose *b* to be equal to *Ae*1, and extending *n* to the full dimension of *A*.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/arnoldi-iteration] Improved versions include one or more shifts, and higher powers of *A* may be applied in a single steps.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/arnoldi-iteration] This is an example of the Rayleigh-Ritz method.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/arnoldi-iteration] It is often observed in practice that some of the Ritz eigenvalues converge to eigenvalues of *A*.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/arnoldi-iteration] Since *H**n* is *n*-by-*n*, it has at most *n* eigenvalues, and not all eigenvalues of *A* can be approximated.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/arnoldi-iteration] Typically, the Ritz eigenvalues converge to the largest eigenvalues of *A*.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/arnoldi-iteration] To get the smallest eigenvalues of *A*, the inverse (operation) of *A* should be used instead.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/arnoldi-iteration] This can be related to the characterization of *H**n* as the matrix whose characteristic polynomial minimizes ||*p*(*A*)*q*1|| in the following way.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/arnoldi-iteration] A good way to get *p*(*A*) small is to choose the polynomial *p* such that *p*(*x*) is small whenever *x* is an eigenvalue of *A*.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/arnoldi-iteration] Hence, the zeros of *p* (and thus the Ritz eigenvalues) will be close to the eigenvalues of *A*.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/arnoldi-iteration] However, the details are not fully understood yet.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/arnoldi-iteration] This is in contrast to the case where *A* is Hermitian.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/arnoldi-iteration] In that situation, the Arnoldi iteration becomes the Lanczos iteration, for which the theory is more complete.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/arnoldi-iteration] Due to practical storage consideration, common implementations of Arnoldi methods typically restart after a fixed number of iterations.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/arnoldi-iteration] One approach is the Implicitly Restarted Arnoldi Method (IRAM) by Lehoucq and Sorensen, which was popularized in the free and open source software package ARPACK.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/arnoldi-iteration] Another approach is the Krylov-Schur Algorithm by G.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/arnoldi-iteration] Stewart, which is more stable and simpler to implement than IRAM.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/divide-and-conquer-eigenvalue-algorithm] This article covers the basic idea of the algorithm as originally proposed by Cuppen in 1981, which is not numerically stable without additional refinements.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/divide-and-conquer-eigenvalue-algorithm] As with most eigenvalue algorithms for Hermitian matrices, divide-and-conquer begins with a reduction to tridiagonal form.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/divide-and-conquer-eigenvalue-algorithm] For an $m\times m$ matrix, the standard method for this, via Householder reflections, takes ${\frac {4}{3}}m^{3}$ floating point operations, or ${\frac {8}{3}}m^{3}$ if eigenvectors are needed as well.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/divide-and-conquer-eigenvalue-algorithm] There are other algorithms, such as the Arnoldi iteration, which may do better for certain classes of matrices; we will not consider this further here.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/divide-and-conquer-eigenvalue-algorithm] In certain cases, it is possible to *deflate* an eigenvalue problem into smaller problems.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/divide-and-conquer-eigenvalue-algorithm] The eigenvalues and eigenvectors of T are simply those of $T_{1}$ and $T_{2}$ , and it will almost always be faster to solve these two smaller problems than to solve the original problem all at once.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/divide-and-conquer-eigenvalue-algorithm] This technique can be used to improve the efficiency of many eigenvalue algorithms, but it has special significance to divide-and-conquer.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/divide-and-conquer-eigenvalue-algorithm] For the rest of this article, we will assume the input to the divide-and-conquer algorithm is an $m\times m$ real symmetric tridiagonal matrix T .
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/divide-and-conquer-eigenvalue-algorithm] The algorithm can be modified for Hermitian matrices.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/divide-and-conquer-eigenvalue-algorithm] The *divide* part of the divide-and-conquer algorithm comes from the realization that a tridiagonal matrix is "almost" block diagonal.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/divide-and-conquer-eigenvalue-algorithm] The size of submatrix $T_{1}$ we will call $n\times n$ , and then $T_{2}$ is $(m-n)\times (m-n)$ .
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/divide-and-conquer-eigenvalue-algorithm] T is almost block diagonal regardless of how n is chosen.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/divide-and-conquer-eigenvalue-algorithm] For efficiency we typically choose $n\approx m/2$ .
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/divide-and-conquer-eigenvalue-algorithm] This can be accomplished with recursive calls to the divide-and-conquer algorithm, although practical implementations often switch to the implicitly shifted QR algorithm for small enough submatrices.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/divide-and-conquer-eigenvalue-algorithm] The *conquer* part of the algorithm is the unintuitive part.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/divide-and-conquer-eigenvalue-algorithm] Given the diagonalizations of the submatrices, calculated above, how do we find the diagonalization of the original matrix?
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/divide-and-conquer-eigenvalue-algorithm] The remaining task has been reduced to finding the eigenvalues of a diagonal matrix plus a rank-one correction.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/divide-and-conquer-eigenvalue-algorithm] Before showing how to do this, let us simplify the notation.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/divide-and-conquer-eigenvalue-algorithm] We are looking for the eigenvalues of the matrix $D+ww^{T}$ , where D is diagonal with distinct entries and w is any vector with nonzero entries.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/divide-and-conquer-eigenvalue-algorithm] The case of a zero entry is simple, since if wi is zero, ( $e_{i}$ ,di) is an eigenpair ( $e_{i}$ is in the standard basis) of $D+ww^{T}$ since $(D+ww^{T})e_{i}=De_{i}=d_{i}e_{i}$ .
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/divide-and-conquer-eigenvalue-algorithm] where q is the corresponding eigenvector.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/divide-and-conquer-eigenvalue-algorithm] Keep in mind that $w^{T}q$ is a nonzero scalar.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/divide-and-conquer-eigenvalue-algorithm] If $w^{T}q$ were to be zero, q would be an eigenvector of D by $(D+ww^{T})q=\lambda q$ .
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/divide-and-conquer-eigenvalue-algorithm] If that were the case, q would contain only one nonzero position since D is distinct diagonal and thus the inner product $w^{T}q$ can not be zero after all.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/divide-and-conquer-eigenvalue-algorithm] This equation is known as the *secular equation*.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/divide-and-conquer-eigenvalue-algorithm] The problem has therefore been reduced to finding the roots of the rational function defined by the left-hand side of this equation.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/divide-and-conquer-eigenvalue-algorithm] Solving the nonlinear secular equation can be done using an iterative technique, such as the Newton–Raphson method.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/divide-and-conquer-eigenvalue-algorithm] However, each root can be found in O(1) iterations, each of which requires $\Theta (m)$ flops (for an m -degree rational function), making the cost of the iterative part of this algorithm $\Theta (m^{2})$ .
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/divide-and-conquer-eigenvalue-algorithm] The fast multipole method has also been employed to solve the secular equation in $\Theta (m\log(m))$ operations.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/divide-and-conquer-eigenvalue-algorithm] W will use the master theorem for divide-and-conquer recurrences to analyze the running time.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/divide-and-conquer-eigenvalue-algorithm] Remember that above we stated we choose $n\approx m/2$ .
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/divide-and-conquer-eigenvalue-algorithm] In the notation of the Master theorem, $a=b=2$ and thus $\log _{b}a=1$ .
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/divide-and-conquer-eigenvalue-algorithm] Above, we pointed out that reducing a Hermitian matrix to tridiagonal form takes ${\frac {4}{3}}m^{3}$ flops.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/divide-and-conquer-eigenvalue-algorithm] This dwarfs the running time of the divide-and-conquer part, and at this point it is not clear what advantage the divide-and-conquer algorithm offers over the QR algorithm (which also takes $\Theta (m^{2})$ flops for tridiagonal matrices).
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/divide-and-conquer-eigenvalue-algorithm] The advantage of divide-and-conquer comes when eigenvectors are needed as well.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/divide-and-conquer-eigenvalue-algorithm] If this is the case, reduction to tridiagonal form takes ${\frac {8}{3}}m^{3}$ , but the second part of the algorithm takes $\Theta (m^{3})$ as well.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/divide-and-conquer-eigenvalue-algorithm] For the QR algorithm with a reasonable target precision, this is $\approx 6m^{3}$ , whereas for divide-and-conquer it is $\approx {\frac {4}{3}}m^{3}$ .
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/divide-and-conquer-eigenvalue-algorithm] The reason for this improvement is that in divide-and-conquer, the $\Theta (m^{3})$ part of the algorithm (multiplying Q matrices) is separate from the iteration, whereas in QR, this must occur in every iterative step.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/divide-and-conquer-eigenvalue-algorithm] Adding the ${\frac {8}{3}}m^{3}$ flops for the reduction, the total improvement is from $\approx 9m^{3}$ to $\approx 4m^{3}$ flops.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/divide-and-conquer-eigenvalue-algorithm] Practical use of the divide-and-conquer algorithm has shown that in most realistic eigenvalue problems, the algorithm actually does better than this.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/divide-and-conquer-eigenvalue-algorithm] The reason is that very often the matrices Q and the vectors z tend to be *numerically sparse*, meaning that they have many entries with values smaller than the floating point precision, allowing for *numerical deflation*, i.e. breaking the problem into uncoupled subproblems.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/divide-and-conquer-eigenvalue-algorithm] The algorithm presented here is the simplest version.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/divide-and-conquer-eigenvalue-algorithm] In many practical implementations, more complicated rank-1 corrections are used to guarantee stability; some variants even use rank-2 corrections.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/divide-and-conquer-eigenvalue-algorithm] There exist specialized root-finding techniques for rational functions that may do better than the Newton-Raphson method in terms of both performance and stability.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/divide-and-conquer-eigenvalue-algorithm] These can be used to improve the iterative part of the divide-and-conquer algorithm.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/divide-and-conquer-eigenvalue-algorithm] The divide-and-conquer algorithm is readily parallelized, and linear algebra computing packages such as LAPACK contain high-quality parallel implementations.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/eigenvalue-algorithm] In numerical analysis, one of the most important problems is designing efficient and stable algorithms for finding the eigenvalues of a matrix.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/eigenvalue-algorithm] These **eigenvalue algorithms** may also find eigenvectors.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/eigenvalue-algorithm] where **v** is a nonzero *n* × 1 column vector, *I* is the *n* × *n* identity matrix, *k* is a positive integer, and both *λ* and **v** are allowed to be complex even when *A* is real.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/eigenvalue-algorithm] When *k* = 1, the vector is called simply an *eigenvector*, and the pair is called an *eigenpair*.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/eigenvalue-algorithm] Any eigenvalue *λ* of *A* has ordinary eigenvectors associated to it, for if *k* is the smallest integer such that (*A* − *λI*)*k* **v** = 0 for a generalized eigenvector **v**, then (*A* − *λI*)*k*−1 **v** is an ordinary eigenvector.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/eigenvalue-algorithm] The value *k* can always be taken as less than or equal to *n*.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/eigenvalue-algorithm] In particular, (*A* − *λI*)*n* **v** = 0 for all generalized eigenvectors **v** associated with *λ*.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/eigenvalue-algorithm] For each eigenvalue λ of *A*, the kernel ker(*A* − *λI*) consists of all eigenvectors associated with *λ* (along with 0), called the *eigenspace* of *λ*, while the vector space ker((*A* − *λI*)*n*) consists of all generalized eigenvectors, and is called the *generalized eigenspace*.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/eigenvalue-algorithm] The *geometric multiplicity* of *λ* is the dimension of its eigenspace.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/eigenvalue-algorithm] The *algebraic multiplicity* of *λ* is the dimension of its generalized eigenspace.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/eigenvalue-algorithm] where det is the determinant function, the *λ**i* are all the distinct eigenvalues of *A* and the *α**i* are the corresponding algebraic multiplicities.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/eigenvalue-algorithm] The function *pA*(*z*) is the *characteristic polynomial* of *A*.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/eigenvalue-algorithm] So the algebraic multiplicity is the multiplicity of the eigenvalue as a zero of the characteristic polynomial.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/eigenvalue-algorithm] Since any eigenvector is also a generalized eigenvector, the geometric multiplicity is less than or equal to the algebraic multiplicity.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/eigenvalue-algorithm] The algebraic multiplicities sum up to *n*, the degree of the characteristic polynomial.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/eigenvalue-algorithm] The equation *pA*(*z*) = 0 is called the *characteristic equation*, as its roots are exactly the eigenvalues of *A*.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/eigenvalue-algorithm] By the Cayley–Hamilton theorem, *A* itself obeys the same equation: *pA*(*A*) = 0.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/eigenvalue-algorithm] As a consequence, the columns of the matrix ${\textstyle \prod _{i\neq j}(A-\lambda _{i}I)^{\alpha _{i}}}$ must be either 0 or generalized eigenvectors of the eigenvalue *λ**j*, since they are annihilated by $(A-\lambda _{j}I)^{\alpha _{j}}$ .
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/eigenvalue-algorithm] In fact, the column space is the generalized eigenspace of *λ**j*.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/eigenvalue-algorithm] Any collection of generalized eigenvectors of distinct eigenvalues is linearly independent, so a basis for all of **C***n* can be chosen consisting of generalized eigenvectors.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/eigenvalue-algorithm] More generally, if *W* is any invertible matrix, and *λ* is an eigenvalue of *A* with generalized eigenvector **v**, then (*W*−1*AW* − *λI*)*k* *W*−*k***v** = 0.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/eigenvalue-algorithm] Thus *λ* is an eigenvalue of *W*−1*AW* with generalized eigenvector *W*−*k***v**.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/eigenvalue-algorithm] That is, similar matrices have the same eigenvalues.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/eigenvalue-algorithm] The adjoint *M** of a complex matrix *M* is the transpose of the conjugate of *M*: *M* * = *M* T.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/eigenvalue-algorithm] A square matrix *A* is called *normal* if it commutes with its adjoint: *A***A* = *AA**.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/eigenvalue-algorithm] It is called *Hermitian* if it is equal to its adjoint: *A** = *A*.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/eigenvalue-algorithm] If *A* has only real elements, then the adjoint is just the transpose, and *A* is Hermitian if and only if it is symmetric.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/eigenvalue-algorithm] When applied to column vectors, the adjoint can be used to define the canonical inner product on **C***n*: **w** ⋅ **v** = **w*** **v**.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/eigenvalue-algorithm] It is possible for a real or complex matrix to have all real eigenvalues without being Hermitian.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/eigenvalue-algorithm] For example, a real triangular matrix has its eigenvalues along its diagonal, but in general is not symmetric.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/eigenvalue-algorithm] Any problem of numeric calculation can be viewed as the evaluation of some function *f* for some input *x*.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/eigenvalue-algorithm] The condition number *κ*(*f*, *x*) of the problem is the ratio of the relative error in the function's output to the relative error in the input, and varies with both the function and the input.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/eigenvalue-algorithm] The condition number describes how error grows during the calculation.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/eigenvalue-algorithm] Its base-10 logarithm tells how many fewer digits of accuracy exist in the result than existed in the input.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/eigenvalue-algorithm] The condition number is a best-case scenario.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/eigenvalue-algorithm] It reflects the instability built into the problem, regardless of how it is solved.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/eigenvalue-algorithm] No algorithm can ever produce more accurate results than indicated by the condition number, except by chance.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/eigenvalue-algorithm] However, a poorly designed algorithm may produce significantly worse results.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/eigenvalue-algorithm] For example, as mentioned below, the problem of finding eigenvalues for normal matrices is always well-conditioned.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/eigenvalue-algorithm] However, the problem of finding the roots of a polynomial can be very ill-conditioned.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/eigenvalue-algorithm] Thus eigenvalue algorithms that work by finding the roots of the characteristic polynomial can be ill-conditioned even when the problem is not.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/eigenvalue-algorithm] For the problem of solving the linear equation *A***v** = **b** where *A* is invertible, the matrix condition number *κ*(*A*−1, **b**) is given by ||*A*||op||*A*−1||op, where || ||op is the operator norm subordinate to the normal Euclidean norm on **C***n*.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/eigenvalue-algorithm] Since this number is independent of **b** and is the same for *A* and *A*−1, it is usually just called the condition number *κ*(*A*) of the matrix *A*.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/eigenvalue-algorithm] This value *κ*(*A*) is also the absolute value of the ratio of the largest singular value of *A* to its smallest.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/eigenvalue-algorithm] For general matrices, the operator norm is often difficult to calculate.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/eigenvalue-algorithm] For this reason, other matrix norms are commonly used to estimate the condition number.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/eigenvalue-algorithm] For the eigenvalue problem, Bauer and Fike proved that if *λ* is an eigenvalue for a diagonalizable *n* × *n* matrix *A* with eigenvector matrix *V*, then the absolute error in calculating *λ* is bounded by the product of *κ*(*V*) and the absolute error in *A*.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/eigenvalue-algorithm] Thus the eigenvalue problem for all normal matrices is well-conditioned.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/eigenvalue-algorithm] The condition number for the problem of finding the eigenspace of a normal matrix *A* corresponding to an eigenvalue *λ* has been shown to be inversely proportional to the minimum distance between *λ* and the other distinct eigenvalues of *A*.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/eigenvalue-algorithm] In particular, the eigenspace problem for normal matrices is well-conditioned for isolated eigenvalues.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/eigenvalue-algorithm] When eigenvalues are not isolated, the best that can be hoped for is to identify the span of all eigenvectors of nearby eigenvalues.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/eigenvalue-algorithm] The most reliable and most widely used algorithm for computing eigenvalues is John G.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/eigenvalue-algorithm] Kublanovskaya's QR algorithm, considered one of the top ten algorithms of 20th century.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/eigenvalue-algorithm] Any monic polynomial is the characteristic polynomial of its companion matrix.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/eigenvalue-algorithm] Therefore, a general algorithm for finding eigenvalues could also be used to find the roots of polynomials.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/eigenvalue-algorithm] The Abel–Ruffini theorem shows that any such algorithm for dimensions greater than 4 must either be infinite, or involve functions of greater complexity than elementary arithmetic operations and fractional powers.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/eigenvalue-algorithm] For this reason algorithms that exactly calculate eigenvalues in a finite number of steps only exist for a few special classes of matrices.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/eigenvalue-algorithm] For general matrices, algorithms are iterative, producing better approximate solutions with each iteration.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/eigenvalue-algorithm] Some algorithms produce every eigenvalue, others will produce a few, or only one.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/eigenvalue-algorithm] However, even the latter algorithms can be used to find all eigenvalues.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/eigenvalue-algorithm] Once an eigenvalue *λ* of a matrix *A* has been identified, it can be used to either direct the algorithm towards a different solution next time, or to reduce the problem to one that no longer has *λ* as a solution.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/eigenvalue-algorithm] Redirection is usually accomplished by shifting: replacing *A* with *A* − *μI* for some constant *μ*.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/eigenvalue-algorithm] The eigenvalue found for *A* − *μI* must have *μ* added back in to get an eigenvalue for *A*.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/eigenvalue-algorithm] For example, for power iteration, *μ* = *λ*.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/eigenvalue-algorithm] Power iteration finds the largest eigenvalue in absolute value, so even when *λ* is only an approximate eigenvalue, power iteration is unlikely to find it a second time.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/eigenvalue-algorithm] Conversely, inverse iteration based methods find the lowest eigenvalue, so *μ* is chosen well away from *λ* and hopefully closer to some other eigenvalue.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/eigenvalue-algorithm] Reduction can be accomplished by restricting *A* to the column space of the matrix *A* − *λI*, which *A* carries to itself.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/eigenvalue-algorithm] Since *A* - *λI* is singular, the column space is of lesser dimension.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/eigenvalue-algorithm] The eigenvalue algorithm can then be applied to the restricted matrix.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/eigenvalue-algorithm] This process can be repeated until all eigenvalues are found.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/eigenvalue-algorithm] If an eigenvalue algorithm does not produce eigenvectors, a common practice is to use an inverse iteration based algorithm with *μ* set to a close approximation to the eigenvalue.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/eigenvalue-algorithm] This will quickly converge to the eigenvector of the closest eigenvalue to *μ*.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/eigenvalue-algorithm] For small matrices, an alternative is to look at the column space of the product of *A* − *λ*'*I* for each of the other eigenvalues *λ*'.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/eigenvalue-algorithm] A formula for the norm of unit eigenvector components of normal matrices was discovered by Robert Thompson in 1966 and rediscovered independently by several others.
