[src:eigenvalue-solvers/eigenvalue-algorithm] A lower Hessenberg matrix is one for which all entries above the superdiagonal are zero.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/eigenvalue-algorithm] Matrices that are both upper and lower Hessenberg are tridiagonal.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/eigenvalue-algorithm] Hessenberg and tridiagonal matrices are the starting points for many eigenvalue algorithms because the zero entries reduce the complexity of the problem.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/eigenvalue-algorithm] Several methods are commonly used to convert a general matrix into a Hessenberg matrix with the same eigenvalues.
