[src:eigenvalue-solvers/jacobi-eigenvalue-algorithm] In numerical linear algebra, the **Jacobi eigenvalue algorithm** is an iterative method for the calculation of the eigenvalues and eigenvectors of a real symmetric matrix (a process known as diagonalization).
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/jacobi-eigenvalue-algorithm] It is named after Carl Gustav Jacob Jacobi, who first proposed the method in 1846, but it only became widely used in the 1950s with the advent of computers.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/jacobi-eigenvalue-algorithm] This algorithm is inherently a dense matrix algorithm: it draws little or no advantage from being applied to a sparse matrix, and it will destroy sparseness by creating fill-in.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/jacobi-eigenvalue-algorithm] Similarly, it will not preserve structures such as being banded of the matrix on which it operates.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/jacobi-eigenvalue-algorithm] Let S be a symmetric matrix, and $G=G(i,j,\theta )$ be a Givens rotation matrix.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/jacobi-eigenvalue-algorithm] In order to optimize this effect, *S**ij* should be the off-diagonal element with the largest absolute value, called the *pivot*.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/jacobi-eigenvalue-algorithm] The Jacobi eigenvalue method repeatedly performs rotations until the matrix becomes almost diagonal.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/jacobi-eigenvalue-algorithm] Then the elements in the diagonal are approximations of the (real) eigenvalues of *S*.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/jacobi-eigenvalue-algorithm] If $p=S_{kl}$ is a pivot element, then by definition $|S_{ij}|\leq |p|$ for $1\leq i,j\leq n,i\neq j$ .
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/jacobi-eigenvalue-algorithm] Let $\Gamma (S)^{2}$ denote the sum of squares of all off-diagonal entries of S .
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/jacobi-eigenvalue-algorithm] A number of N Jacobi rotations is called a sweep; let $S^{\sigma }$ denote the result.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/jacobi-eigenvalue-algorithm] that is, the sequence of sweeps converges at least linearly with a factor ≈ $e^{1/2}$ .
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/jacobi-eigenvalue-algorithm] However the following result of Schönhage yields locally quadratic convergence.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/jacobi-eigenvalue-algorithm] To this end let *S* have *m* distinct eigenvalues $\lambda _{1},...,\lambda _{m}$ with multiplicities $\nu _{1},...,\nu _{m}$ and let *d* > 0 be the smallest distance of two different eigenvalues.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/jacobi-eigenvalue-algorithm] Each Givens rotation can be done in $O(n)$ steps when the pivot element *p* is known.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/jacobi-eigenvalue-algorithm] However the search for *p* requires inspection of all *N* ≈ ⁠1/2⁠ *n*2 off-diagonal elements, which means this search dominates the overall complexity and pushes the computational complexity of a sweep in the classical Jacobi algorithm to $O(n^{4})$ .
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/jacobi-eigenvalue-algorithm] Competing algorithms attain $O(n^{3})$ complexity for a full diagonalisation.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/jacobi-eigenvalue-algorithm] We can reduce the complexity of finding the pivot element from O(*N*) to O(*n*) if we introduce an additional index array $m_{1},\,\dots \,,\,m_{n-1}$ with the property that $m_{i}$ is the index of the largest element in row *i*, (*i* = 1, ..., *n* − 1) of the current *S*.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/jacobi-eigenvalue-algorithm] Then the indices of the pivot (*k*, *l*) must be one of the pairs $(i,m_{i})$ .
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/jacobi-eigenvalue-algorithm] Also the updating of the index array can be done in O(*n*) average-case complexity: First, the maximum entry in the updated rows *k* and *l* can be found in O(*n*) steps.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/jacobi-eigenvalue-algorithm] In the other rows *i*, only the entries in columns *k* and *l* change.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/jacobi-eigenvalue-algorithm] Looping over these rows, if $m_{i}$ is neither *k* nor *l*, it suffices to compare the old maximum at $m_{i}$ to the new entries and update $m_{i}$ if necessary.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/jacobi-eigenvalue-algorithm] If $m_{i}$ should be equal to *k* or *l* and the corresponding entry decreased during the update, the maximum over row *i* has to be found from scratch in O(*n*) complexity.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/jacobi-eigenvalue-algorithm] However, this will happen on average only once per rotation.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/jacobi-eigenvalue-algorithm] Thus, each rotation has O(*n*) and one sweep O(*n*3) average-case complexity, which is equivalent to one matrix multiplication.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/jacobi-eigenvalue-algorithm] Additionally the $m_{i}$ must be initialized before the process starts, which can be done in *n*2 steps.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/jacobi-eigenvalue-algorithm] Typically the Jacobi method converges within numerical precision after a small number of sweeps.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/jacobi-eigenvalue-algorithm] Note that multiple eigenvalues reduce the number of iterations since $N_{S}<N$ .
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/jacobi-eigenvalue-algorithm] An alternative approach is to forego the search entirely, and simply have each sweep pivot every off-diagonal element once, in some predetermined order.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/jacobi-eigenvalue-algorithm] It has been shown that this *cyclic Jacobi* attains quadratic convergence, just like the classical Jacobi.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/jacobi-eigenvalue-algorithm] The opportunity for parallelisation that is particular to Jacobi is based on combining cyclic Jacobi with the observation that Givens rotations for disjoint sets of indices commute, so that several can be applied in parallel.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/jacobi-eigenvalue-algorithm] Two processors can perform both rotations in parallel, because no matrix element is accessed for both.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/jacobi-eigenvalue-algorithm] Partitioning the set of index pairs of a sweep into classes that are pairwise disjoint is equivalent to partitioning the edge set of a complete graph into matchings, which is the same thing as edge colouring it; each colour class then becomes a round within the sweep.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/jacobi-eigenvalue-algorithm] The minimal number of rounds is the chromatic index of the complete graph, and equals n for odd n but $n-1$ for even n .
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/jacobi-eigenvalue-algorithm] For even n one may create $n-1$ rounds $k=0,1,\dotsc ,n-2$ where a pair $\{i,j\}$ for $1\leqslant i<j\leqslant n-1$ goes into round $(i+j){\bmod {(}}n-1)$ and additionally a pair $\{i,n\}$ for $1\leqslant i\leqslant n-1$ goes into round $2i{\bmod {(}}n-1)$ .
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/jacobi-eigenvalue-algorithm] This brings the time complexity of a sweep down from $O(n^{3})$ to $O(n^{2})$ , if $n/2$ processors are available.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/jacobi-eigenvalue-algorithm] A round would consist of each processor first calculating $(c,s)$ for its rotation, and then applying the rotation from the left (rotating between rows).
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/jacobi-eigenvalue-algorithm] Next, the processors synchronise before applying the transpose rotation from the right (rotating between columns), and finally synchronising again.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/jacobi-eigenvalue-algorithm] A matrix element may be accessed by two processors during a round, but not by both during the same half of this round.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/jacobi-eigenvalue-algorithm] Further parallelisation is possible by dividing the work for a single rotation between several processors, but that might be getting too fine-grained to be practical.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/jacobi-eigenvalue-algorithm] The following algorithm is a description of the Jacobi method in math-like notation.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/jacobi-eigenvalue-algorithm] It calculates a vector *e* which contains the eigenvalues and a matrix *E* which contains the corresponding eigenvectors; that is, $e_{i}$ is an eigenvalue and the column $E_{i}$ an orthonormal eigenvector for $e_{i}$ , *i* = 1, ..., *n*.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/lanczos-algorithm] Although computationally efficient in principle, the method as initially formulated was not useful, due to its numerical instability.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/lanczos-algorithm] In 1970, Ojalvo and Newman showed how to make the method numerically stable and applied it to the solution of very large engineering structures subjected to dynamic loading.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/lanczos-algorithm] Soon thereafter their work was followed by Paige, who also provided an error analysis.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/lanczos-algorithm] In 1988, Ojalvo produced a more detailed history of this algorithm and an efficient eigenvalue error test.
