[src:eigenvalue-solvers/lanczos-algorithm] Not counting the matrix–vector multiplication, each iteration does $O(n)$ arithmetical operations.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/lanczos-algorithm] The matrix–vector multiplication can be done in $O(dn)$ arithmetical operations where d is the average number of nonzero elements in a row.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/lanczos-algorithm] The total complexity is thus $O(dmn)$ , or $O(dn^{2})$ if $m=n$ ; the Lanczos algorithm can be very fast for sparse matrices.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/lanczos-algorithm] Schemes for improving numerical stability are typically judged against this high performance.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/lanczos-algorithm] The vectors $v_{j}$ are called *Lanczos vectors*.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/lanczos-algorithm] The vector $w_{j}'$ is not used after $w_{j}$ is computed, and the vector $w_{j}$ is not used after $v_{j+1}$ is computed.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/lanczos-algorithm] Hence one may use the same storage for all three.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/lanczos-algorithm] Likewise, if only the tridiagonal matrix T is sought, then the raw iteration does not need $v_{j-1}$ after having computed $w_{j}$ , although some schemes for improving the numerical stability would need it later on.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/lanczos-algorithm] Sometimes the subsequent Lanczos vectors are recomputed from $v_{1}$ when needed.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/lanczos-algorithm] Nonetheless, applying the Lanczos algorithm is often a significant step forward in computing the eigendecomposition.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/lanczos-algorithm] Thus the Lanczos algorithm transforms the eigendecomposition problem for A into the eigendecomposition problem for T .
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/lanczos-algorithm] Some general eigendecomposition algorithms, notably the QR algorithm, are known to converge faster for tridiagonal matrices than for general matrices.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/lanczos-algorithm] Asymptotic complexity of tridiagonal QR is $O(m^{2})$ just as for the divide-and-conquer algorithm (though the constant factor may be different); since the eigenvectors together have $m^{2}$ elements, this is asymptotically optimal.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/lanczos-algorithm] Even algorithms whose convergence rates are unaffected by unitary transformations, such as the power method and inverse iteration, may enjoy low-level performance benefits from being applied to the tridiagonal matrix T rather than the original matrix A .
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/lanczos-algorithm] Since T is very sparse with all nonzero elements in highly predictable positions, it permits compact storage with excellent performance vis-à-vis caching.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/lanczos-algorithm] Likewise, T is a real matrix with all eigenvectors and eigenvalues real, whereas A in general may have complex elements and eigenvectors, so real arithmetic is sufficient for finding the eigenvectors and eigenvalues of T .
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/lanczos-algorithm] The combination of good performance for sparse matrices and the ability to compute several (without computing all) eigenvalues are the main reasons for choosing to use the Lanczos algorithm.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/lanczos-algorithm] Though the eigenproblem is often the motivation for applying the Lanczos algorithm, the operation the algorithm primarily performs is tridiagonalization of a matrix, for which numerically stable Householder transformations have been favoured since the 1950s.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/lanczos-algorithm] During the 1960s the Lanczos algorithm was disregarded.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/lanczos-algorithm] Interest in it was rejuvenated by the Kaniel–Paige convergence theory and the development of methods to prevent numerical instability, but the Lanczos algorithm remains the alternative algorithm that one tries only if Householder is not satisfactory.
