[src:eigenvalue-solvers/lanczos-algorithm] The convergence for the Lanczos algorithm is often orders of magnitude faster than that for the power iteration algorithm.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/lanczos-algorithm] The bounds for $\theta _{1}$ come from the above interpretation of eigenvalues as extreme values of the Rayleigh quotient $r(x)$ .
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/lanczos-algorithm] Since $\lambda _{1}$ is a priori the maximum of r on the whole of $\mathbb {C} ^{n},$ whereas $\theta _{1}$ is merely the maximum on an m -dimensional Krylov subspace, we trivially get $\lambda _{1}\geqslant \theta _{1}$ .
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/lanczos-algorithm] Conversely, any point x in that Krylov subspace provides a lower bound $r(x)$ for $\theta _{1}$ , so if a point can be exhibited for which $\lambda _{1}-r(x)$ is small then this provides a tight bound on $\theta _{1}$ .
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/lanczos-algorithm] so any element of it can be expressed as $p(A)v_{1}$ for some polynomial p of degree at most $m-1$ ; the coefficients of that polynomial are simply the coefficients in the linear combination of the vectors $v_{1},Av_{1},A^{2}v_{1},\ldots ,A^{m-1}v_{1}$ .
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/lanczos-algorithm] The polynomial we want will turn out to have real coefficients, but for the moment we should allow also for complex coefficients, and we will write $p^{*}$ for the polynomial obtained by complex conjugating all coefficients of p .
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/lanczos-algorithm] A key difference between numerator and denominator here is that the $k=1$ term vanishes in the numerator, but not in the denominator.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/lanczos-algorithm] Thus if one can pick p to be large at $\lambda _{1}$ but small at all other eigenvalues, one will get a tight bound on the error $\lambda _{1}-\theta _{1}$ .
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/lanczos-algorithm] Since A has many more eigenvalues than p has coefficients, this may seem a tall order, but one way to meet it is to use Chebyshev polynomials.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/lanczos-algorithm] Writing $c_{k}$ for the degree k Chebyshev polynomial of the first kind (that which satisfies $c_{k}(\cos x)=\cos(kx)$ for all x ), we have a polynomial which stays in the range $[-1,1]$ on the known interval $[-1,1]$ but grows rapidly outside it.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/lanczos-algorithm] With some scaling of the argument, we can have it map all eigenvalues except $\lambda _{1}$ into $[-1,1]$ .
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/lanczos-algorithm] (i.e., the ratio of the first eigengap to the diameter of the rest of the spectrum) is thus of key importance for the convergence rate here.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/lanczos-algorithm] The convergence rate is thus controlled chiefly by R , since this bound shrinks by a factor $R^{-2}$ for each extra iteration.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/lanczos-algorithm] Under that constraint, the case that most favours the power method is that $\lambda _{n}=-\lambda _{2}$ , so consider that.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/lanczos-algorithm] which shrinks by a factor of $(1+2\rho )^{-2}$ for each iteration.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/lanczos-algorithm] The difference thus boils down to that between $1+2\rho$ and $R=1+2\rho +2{\sqrt {\rho ^{2}+\rho }}$ .
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/lanczos-algorithm] In the $\rho \gg 1$ region, the latter is more like $1+4\rho$ , and performs like the power method would with an eigengap twice as large; a notable improvement.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/lanczos-algorithm] The more challenging case is however that of $\rho \ll 1,$ in which $R\approx 1+2{\sqrt {\rho }}$ is an even larger improvement on the eigengap; the $\rho \gg 1$ region is where the Lanczos algorithm convergence-wise makes the *smallest* improvement on the power method.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/lanczos-algorithm] Stability means how much the algorithm will be affected (i.e. will it produce the approximate result close to the original one) if there are small numerical errors introduced and accumulated.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/lanczos-algorithm] Numerical stability is the central criterion for judging the usefulness of implementing an algorithm on a computer with roundoff.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/lanczos-algorithm] For the Lanczos algorithm, it can be proved that with *exact arithmetic*, the set of vectors $v_{1},v_{2},\cdots ,v_{m+1}$ constructs an *orthonormal* basis, and the eigenvalues/vectors solved are good approximations to those of the original matrix.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/lanczos-algorithm] However, in practice (as the calculations are performed in floating point arithmetic where inaccuracy is inevitable), the orthogonality is quickly lost and in some cases the new vector could even be linearly dependent on the set that is already constructed.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/lanczos-algorithm] As a result, some of the eigenvalues of the resultant tridiagonal matrix may not be approximations to the original matrix.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/lanczos-algorithm] Therefore, the Lanczos algorithm is not very stable.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/lanczos-algorithm] Users of this algorithm must be able to find and remove those "spurious" eigenvalues.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/lanczos-algorithm] Recover the orthogonality after the basis is generated.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/lanczos-algorithm] After the good and "spurious" eigenvalues are all identified, remove the spurious ones.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/lanczos-algorithm] Variations on the Lanczos algorithm exist where the vectors involved are tall, narrow matrices instead of vectors and the normalizing constants are small square matrices.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/lanczos-algorithm] These are called "block" Lanczos algorithms and can be much faster on computers with large numbers of registers and long memory-fetch times.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/lanczos-algorithm] Many implementations of the Lanczos algorithm restart after a certain number of iterations.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/lanczos-algorithm] One of the most influential restarted variations is the implicitly restarted Lanczos method, which is implemented in ARPACK.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/lanczos-algorithm] This has led into a number of other restarted variations such as restarted Lanczos bidiagonalization.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/lanczos-algorithm] Another successful restarted variation is the Thick-Restart Lanczos method, which has been implemented in a software package called TRLan.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/lanczos-algorithm] Lanczos algorithms are very attractive because the multiplication by $A\,$ is the only large-scale linear operation.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/lanczos-algorithm] Since weighted-term text retrieval engines implement just this operation, the Lanczos algorithm can be applied efficiently to text documents (see latent semantic indexing).
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/lanczos-algorithm] Eigenvectors are also important for large-scale ranking methods such as the HITS algorithm developed by Jon Kleinberg, or the PageRank algorithm used by Google.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/lanczos-algorithm] Lanczos algorithms are also used in condensed matter physics as a method for solving Hamiltonians of strongly correlated electron systems, as well as in shell model codes in nuclear physics.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/lanczos-algorithm] The NAG Library contains several routines for the solution of large scale linear systems and eigenproblems which use the Lanczos algorithm.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/lanczos-algorithm] ARPACK (FORTRAN 77, also available in MATLAB[1], GNU Octave(eigs), Julia[2], and Python via the SciPy[3] package) focuses on eigenvalue problems, and supports both stored and implicit matrices.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/lanczos-algorithm] A Matlab implementation of the Lanczos algorithm (note precision issues) is available as a part of the Gaussian Belief Propagation Matlab Package.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/lanczos-algorithm] The GraphLab collaborative filtering library incorporates a large scale parallel implementation of the Lanczos algorithm (in C++) for multicore.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/lanczos-algorithm] Julia implementations of Lanczos and related Krylov methods can be found in Krylov.jl, KrylovKit.jl, IterativeSolvers.jl, and ArnoldiMethod.jl.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/lanczos-algorithm] The PRIMME library also implements a Lanczos-like algorithm.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/lanczos-algorithm] An open source Python package Leymosun implements Lanczos algorithm in the context of Krylov Complexity in pure Python: Its function called *lanczos* will generate Krylov bases and the coefficients.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] In numerical linear algebra, the **QR algorithm** or **QR iteration** is an eigenvalue algorithm: that is, a procedure to calculate the eigenvalues and eigenvectors of a matrix.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] The QR algorithm was developed in the late 1950s by John G.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] The basic idea is to perform a QR decomposition, writing the matrix as a product of an orthogonal matrix and an upper triangular matrix, multiply the factors in the reverse order, and iterate.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] Formally, let *A* be a real matrix of which we want to compute the eigenvalues, and let *A*0 := *A*.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] At the k-th step (starting with *k* = 0), we compute the QR decomposition *A**k* = *Q**k* *R**k* where *Q**k* is an orthogonal matrix (i.e., *Q*T = *Q*−1) and *R**k* is an upper triangular matrix.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] The algorithm is numerically stable because it proceeds by *orthogonal* similarity transforms.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] Under certain conditions, the matrices *A**k* converge to a triangular matrix, the Schur form of *A*.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] The eigenvalues of a triangular matrix are listed on the diagonal, and the eigenvalue problem is solved.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] In testing for convergence it is impractical to require exact zeros, but the Gershgorin circle theorem provides a bound on the error.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] If the matrices converge, then the eigenvalues along the diagonal will appear according to their geometric multiplicity.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] To guarantee convergence, A must be a symmetric matrix, and for all non zero eigenvalues $\lambda$ there must not be a corresponding eigenvalue $-\lambda$ .
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] Due to the fact that a single QR iteration has a cost of ${\mathcal {O}}(n^{3})$ and the convergence is linear, the standard QR algorithm is extremely expensive to compute, especially considering it is not guaranteed to converge.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] In the above crude form the iterations are relatively expensive.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] (For QR decomposition, the Householder reflectors are multiplied only on the left, but for the Hessenberg case they are multiplied on both left and right.) Determining the QR decomposition of an upper Hessenberg matrix costs ${\textstyle 6n^{2}+{\mathcal {O}}(n)}$ arithmetic operations.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] Moreover, because the Hessenberg form is already nearly upper-triangular (it has just one nonzero entry below each diagonal), using it as a starting point reduces the number of steps required for convergence of the QR algorithm.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] If the original matrix is symmetric, then the upper Hessenberg matrix is also symmetric and thus tridiagonal, and so are all the *A**k*.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] In this case reaching Hessenberg form costs ${\textstyle {\tfrac {4}{3}}n^{3}+{\mathcal {O}}(n^{2})}$ arithmetic operations using a technique based on Householder reduction.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] Determining the QR decomposition of a symmetric tridiagonal matrix costs ${\mathcal {O}}(n)$ operations.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] The purpose of the QR iteration step is to shrink one of these $a_{k,k-1}$ elements so that effectively a small block along the diagonal is split off from the bulk of the matrix.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] In the case of a real eigenvalue that is usually the $1\times 1$ block in the lower right corner (in which case element $a_{nn}$ holds that eigenvalue), whereas in the case of a pair of conjugate complex eigenvalues it is the $2\times 2$ block in the lower right corner.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] The rate of convergence depends on the separation between eigenvalues, so a practical algorithm will use shifts, either explicit or implicit, to increase separation and accelerate convergence.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] A typical symmetric QR algorithm isolates each eigenvalue (then reduces the size of the matrix) with only one or two iterations, making it efficient as well as robust.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] This produces the upper triangular matrix $R=G_{n-1}\dotsb G_{1}(A-\mu I)$ .
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] The orthogonal factor Q would be $G_{1}^{\mathrm {T} }G_{2}^{\mathrm {T} }\dotsb G_{n-1}^{\mathrm {T} }$ , but it is neither necessary nor efficient to produce that explicitly.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] This produces the matrix $RQ=RG_{1}^{\mathrm {T} }G_{2}^{\mathrm {T} }\dotsb G_{n-1}^{\mathrm {T} }$ , which is again on Hessenberg form.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] Finally undo the shift by adding $\mu$ to all diagonal entries.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] Since Q commutes with I , we have that $A'=Q^{\mathrm {T} }(A-\mu I)Q+\mu I=Q^{\mathrm {T} }AQ$ .
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] The purpose of the shift is to change which Givens rotations are chosen.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] It is not necessary to exhibit $\theta$ ; the factors c and s can be determined directly from elements in the matrix $G_{i}$ should act on.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] Nor is it necessary to produce the whole matrix; multiplication (from the left) by $G_{i}$ only affects rows i and $i+1$ , so it is easier to just update those two rows in place.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] Likewise, for the Step 3 multiplication by $G_{i}^{\mathrm {T} }$ from the right, it is sufficient to remember i , c , and s .
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] If $|h_{n-1,n-1}|\gg |h_{n,n-1}|$ , as is typically the case when we approach convergence, then $c\approx 1$ and $|s|\ll 1$ .
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] But now we reach Step 3, and need to start rotating data between columns.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] Practically that means $O(1)$ iterations per eigenvalue suffice for convergence, and thus overall we can complete in $O(n)$ QR steps, each of which does a mere $O(n^{2})$ arithmetic operations (or as little as $O(n)$ operations, in the case that A is symmetric).
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] The basic QR algorithm can be visualized in the case where *A* is a positive-definite symmetric matrix.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] In that case, *A* can be depicted as an ellipse in 2 dimensions or an ellipsoid in higher dimensions.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] The relationship between the input to the algorithm and a single iteration can then be depicted as in Figure 1 (click to see an animation).
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] Note that the LR algorithm is depicted alongside the QR algorithm.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] A single iteration causes the ellipse to tilt or "fall" towards the x-axis.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] In the event where the large semi-axis of the ellipse is parallel to the x-axis, one iteration of QR does nothing.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] Another situation where the algorithm "does nothing" is when the large semi-axis is parallel to the y-axis instead of the x-axis.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] In that event, the ellipse can be thought of as balancing precariously without being able to fall in either direction.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] In both situations, the matrix is diagonal.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] A situation where an iteration of the algorithm "does nothing" is called a fixed point.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] The strategy employed by the algorithm is iteration towards a fixed-point.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] Observe that one fixed point is stable while the other is unstable.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] If the ellipse were tilted away from the unstable fixed point by a very small amount, one iteration of QR would cause the ellipse to tilt away from the fixed point instead of towards.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] Eventually though, the algorithm would converge to a different fixed point, but it would take a long time.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] It's worth pointing out that finding even a single eigenvector of a symmetric matrix is not computable (in exact real arithmetic according to the definitions in computable analysis).
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] This difficulty exists whenever the multiplicities of a matrix's eigenvalues are not knowable.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] On the other hand, the same problem does not exist for finding eigenvalues.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] The eigenvalues of a matrix are always computable.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] We will now discuss how these difficulties manifest in the basic QR algorithm.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] Recall that the ellipses represent positive-definite symmetric matrices.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] As the two eigenvalues of the input matrix approach each other, the input ellipse changes into a circle.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] A circle corresponds to a multiple of the identity matrix.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] A near-circle corresponds to a near-multiple of the identity matrix whose eigenvalues are nearly equal to the diagonal entries of the matrix.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] Therefore, the problem of approximately finding the eigenvalues is shown to be easy in that case.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] But notice what happens to the semi-axes of the ellipses.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] An iteration of QR (or LR) tilts the semi-axes less and less as the input ellipse gets closer to being a circle.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] The eigenvectors can only be known when the semi-axes are parallel to the x-axis and y-axis.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] The number of iterations needed to achieve near-parallelism increases without bound as the input ellipse becomes more circular.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] While it may be impossible to compute the eigendecomposition of an arbitrary symmetric matrix, it is always possible to perturb the matrix by an arbitrarily small amount and compute the eigendecomposition of the resulting matrix.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] In the case when the matrix is depicted as a near-circle, the matrix can be replaced with one whose depiction is a perfect circle.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] In that case, the matrix is a multiple of the identity matrix, and its eigendecomposition is immediate.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] Be aware though that the resulting eigenbasis can be quite far from the original eigenbasis.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] The slowdown when the ellipse gets more circular has a converse: It turns out that when the ellipse gets more stretched - and less circular - then the rotation of the ellipse becomes faster.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] Such a stretch can be induced when the matrix M which the ellipse represents gets replaced with $M-\lambda I$ where $\lambda$ is approximately the smallest eigenvalue of M .
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] In this case, the ratio of the two semi-axes of the ellipse approaches $\infty$ .
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] In higher dimensions, shifting like this makes the length of the smallest semi-axis of an ellipsoid small relative to the other semi-axes, which speeds up convergence to the smallest eigenvalue, but does not speed up convergence to the other eigenvalues.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] This becomes useless when the smallest eigenvalue is fully determined, so the matrix must then be *deflated*, which simply means removing its last row and column.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] The issue with the unstable fixed point also needs to be addressed.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] The shifting heuristic is often designed to deal with this problem as well: Practical shifts are often discontinuous and randomised.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] Wilkinson's shift—which is well-suited for symmetric matrices like the ones we're visualising—is in particular discontinuous.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] In modern computational practice, the QR algorithm is performed in an implicit version which makes the use of multiple shifts easier to introduce.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] Then successive Householder transformations of size $r+1$ are performed in order to return the working matrix $A_{k}$ to upper Hessenberg form.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] This operation is known as *bulge chasing*, due to the peculiar shape of the non-zero entries of the matrix along the steps of the algorithm.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] As in the first version, deflation is performed as soon as one of the sub-diagonal entries of $A_{k}$ is sufficiently small.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] Since in the modern implicit version of the procedure no QR decompositions are explicitly performed, some authors, for instance Watkins, suggested changing its name to *Francis algorithm*.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] Golub and Van Loan use the term *Francis QR step*.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] The QR algorithm can be seen as a more sophisticated variation of the basic "power" eigenvalue algorithm.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] Recall that the power algorithm repeatedly multiplies *A* times a single vector, normalizing after each iteration.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] The vector converges to an eigenvector of the largest eigenvalue.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] Instead, the QR algorithm works with a complete basis of vectors, using QR decomposition to renormalize (and orthogonalize).
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] For a symmetric matrix *A*, upon convergence, *AQ* = *QΛ*, where *Λ* is the diagonal matrix of eigenvalues to which *A* converged, and where *Q* is a composite of all the orthogonal similarity transforms required to get there.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] Thus the columns of *Q* are the eigenvectors.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] The QR algorithm was preceded by the *LR algorithm*, which uses the LU decomposition instead of the QR decomposition.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] The QR algorithm is more stable, so the LR algorithm is rarely used nowadays.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] However, it represents an important step in the development of the QR algorithm.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] The LR algorithm was developed in the early 1950s by Heinz Rutishauser, who worked at that time as a research assistant of Eduard Stiefel at ETH Zurich.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] Stiefel suggested that Rutishauser use the sequence of moments *y*0T *A**k* *x*0, *k* = 0, 1, ...
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] (where *x*0 and *y*0 are arbitrary vectors) to find the eigenvalues of *A*.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] Rutishauser took an algorithm of Alexander Aitken for this task and developed it into the *quotient–difference algorithm* or *qd algorithm*.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] After arranging the computation in a suitable shape, he discovered that the qd algorithm is in fact the iteration *A**k* = *L**k**U**k* (LU decomposition), *A**k*+1 = *U**k**L**k*, applied on a tridiagonal matrix, from which the LR algorithm follows.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] One variant of the *QR algorithm*, *the Golub-Kahan-Reinsch* algorithm starts with reducing a general matrix into a bidiagonal one.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] This variant of the *QR algorithm* for the computation of singular values was first described by Golub & Kahan (1965).
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] The LAPACK subroutine DBDSQR implements this iterative method, with some modifications to cover the case where the singular values are very small (Demmel & Kahan 1990).
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] Together with a first step using Householder reflections and, if appropriate, QR decomposition, this forms the DGESVD routine for the computation of the singular value decomposition.
[src:eigenvalue-solvers/qr-algorithm] The QR algorithm can also be implemented in infinite dimensions with corresponding convergence results.
